description: From Middle English deluden, from Latin dēlūdō (“mock, deceive”), from de + lūdō ("I make sport of, I mock"). See ludicrous.

verbs.description: delude (third-person singular simple present deludes, present participle deluding, simple past and past participle deluded)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To deceive into believing something which is false; to lead into error; to dupe.
